---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const meta = {
  title: 'Framer Review 2025: Best for Designers, But Is It Worth It?',
  description: 'Framer website builder: Free tier available, Pro from $5/month, Basic from $15/month, CMS from $25/month. Visual builder with React-like components. Fast performance, SEO-friendly, but limited e-commerce. Best for portfolios, marketing sites. Webflow alternative with modern approach. Steeper learning curve than Wix, more flexible than Squarespace.',
  image: '/og-image.svg',
  keywords: ['Framer review', 'Framer pricing', 'Framer vs Webflow', 'website builder', 'no-code'],
};
---

<Layout {...meta}>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-[#0055FF]/5 to-[#7C3AED]/5 py-12 sm:py-16 md:py-20">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4">
      <p class="text-[10px] sm:text-xs font-black text-[#0055FF] mb-4 tracking-[0.3em] uppercase">
        Website Builder Review · 2025
      </p>

      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-black mb-6 leading-tight">
        Framer Review 2025
      </h1>

      <p class="text-lg sm:text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-8">
        Framer is the modern website builder for designers. Visual interface that feels like design tools. Components that work like React code. Performance that beats most competitors. But it's not for everyone. E-commerce is weak. Learning curve is steeper than Wix. The free tier lets you prototype, but you'll pay for serious sites. Here's the honest truth about whether Framer is worth it.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-white bg-opacity-50 border-2 border-gray-300 rounded-xl p-6">
        <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">
          Quick answer: Choose Framer if you're a designer who wants visual control without coding. Skip it if you need serious e-commerce or have zero design sense. Framer sits between Squarespace (easier) and Webflow (more powerful). Best for portfolios, marketing sites, and product landing pages.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What Framer Does Well -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      What Framer Does Well
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Visual Design That Feels Natural</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Framer's interface feels like Figma or Sketch, not a website builder.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> If you've used design tools, Framer feels familiar. Drag, drop, resize, style - all visual. No fighting with a template you can't customize. You have pixel-perfect control without writing code.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Components and Reusability</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Create once, use everywhere. Framer uses components like React does.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Design a button, save it as component, reuse across your site. Update once, changes apply everywhere. This is how modern web design works. Most website builders don't have this.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Performance Built In</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Framer sites load fast. Core Web Vitals scores are strong.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Site speed affects SEO and user experience. Framer generates optimized code automatically. You don't need to be a performance expert. Your site just loads fast.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">CMS and Dynamic Content</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Content management included on paid plans. Collections, filtering, dynamic pages.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Build blogs, portfolios, job boards - anything that needs dynamic content. No manual page creation. Add content to CMS, pages generate automatically.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Figma to Website</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Import Figma designs directly. Layers, frames, styles - all preserved.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Design in Figma, export to Framer. Massive time saver. No rebuilding from scratch. You iterate in design tools, then publish.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Interactions and Animations</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Create scroll effects, hover states, page transitions visually.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Modern websites feel alive with micro-interactions. Framer makes this accessible without coding. Scroll animations, hover effects, smooth transitions - all doable visually.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What Framer Doesn't Do Well -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      What Framer Doesn't Do Well
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">E-commerce is Weak</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Basic selling only. No shopping cart, no inventory management.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Reality:</strong> You can add Stripe buttons and sell things. But this isn't a real e-commerce platform. No abandoned cart recovery, no complex product options, no inventory tracking. For serious stores, use Shopify.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Steeper Learning Curve</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">More complex than Squarespace or Wix. Concepts like components confuse beginners.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Reality:</strong> If you've never used design tools, Framer feels overwhelming. The interface is powerful but not simple. You need to understand design fundamentals to get the most out of it.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Fewer Templates</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Template selection is smaller than competitors.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Reality:</strong> Framer expects you to design, not just customize templates. You can start from templates, but the selection isn't huge. This is a feature for designers, bug for beginners.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">No Native Blogging</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Blogging exists but feels like an afterthought.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Reality:</strong> The CMS can power a blog. But it lacks WordPress-style features. No native commenting, no advanced blogging workflows. Fine for simple blogs, not for serious content marketers.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Platform Lock-In</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">You can't export your site easily. Migration is difficult.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>Reality:</strong> Unlike Webflow, Framer doesn't let you export code. If you leave Framer, you rebuild your site. This is true for most builders, but worth knowing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Pricing -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      Framer Pricing
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-100 border-2 border-gray-300 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Free - $0</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">For prototyping and personal projects.</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• Framer branding on your site</li>
          <li>• Limited to 1 page</li>
          <li>• CMS limited to 10 items</li>
          <li>• Framer domain (yourname.framer.website)</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Best for:</strong> Testing Framer, portfolios, hobby projects.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Pro - $5/month (billed annually) or $7/month</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">For personal sites and portfolios.</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• Custom domain</li>
          <li>• No Framer branding</li>
          <li>• Up to 3 pages</li>
          <li>• CMS limited to 50 items</li>
          <li>• SSL certificate included</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Best for:</strong> Personal portfolios, resumes, simple sites.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Basic - $15/month (billed annually) or $20/month</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">For small business sites.</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• Unlimited pages</li>
          <li>• CMS limited to 1,000 items</li>
          <li>• Analytics included</li>
          <li>• Figma import</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Best for:</strong> Small business sites, portfolios with CMS needs.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">CMS - $25/month (billed annually) or $35/month</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">For content-heavy sites.</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• Unlimited pages</li>
          <li>• CMS unlimited items</li>
          <li>• Localization (multi-language)</li>
          <li>• Everything in Basic</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Best for:</strong> Blogs, job boards, directories, portfolios with lots of content.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">CMS + Team - $40/month (billed annually) or $55/month</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">For teams and agencies.</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• Everything in CMS</li>
          <li>• Team collaboration</li>
          <li>• Role-based permissions</li>
          <li>• Priority support</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Best for:</strong> Agencies, teams building client sites.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Framer vs Competitors -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      Framer vs Competitors
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-purple-50 border-2 border-purple-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Framer vs Webflow</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Framer is more visual. Webflow is more powerful.</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>Framer:</strong> Easier to learn, Figma-like interface, faster workflow</li>
          <li>• <strong>Webflow:</strong> More control, code export, stronger e-commerce, more mature</li>
          <li>• <strong>Choose Framer if:</strong> You're a designer who wants visual speed</li>
          <li>• <strong>Choose Webflow if:</strong> You need maximum control or e-commerce</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-purple-50 border-2 border-purple-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Framer vs Squarespace</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Framer is more flexible. Squarespace is easier.</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>Framer:</strong> More design control, components, better performance</li>
          <li>• <strong>Squarespace:</strong> Easier, better templates, stronger e-commerce</li>
          <li>• <strong>Choose Framer if:</strong> You're a designer who wants control</li>
          <li>• <strong>Choose Squarespace if:</strong> You want something that looks good fast</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-purple-50 border-2 border-purple-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Framer vs Wix</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Framer is for designers. Wix is for everyone.</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>Framer:</strong> Better performance, components, more professional output</li>
          <li>• <strong>Wix:</strong> Easier, more templates, more app integrations</li>
          <li>• <strong>Choose Framer if:</strong> You care about design quality and performance</li>
          <li>• <strong>Choose Wix if:</strong> You want maximum flexibility with zero learning</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Who Should Use Framer -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      Who Should Use Framer?
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">✅ Perfect For:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>Designers:</strong> Figma users who want to build their own sites</li>
          <li>• <strong>Portfolios:</strong> Showcasing design work beautifully</li>
          <li>• <strong>Marketing sites:</strong> Product pages, landing pages, startup sites</li>
          <li>• <strong>Agencies:</strong> Building client sites quickly with visual control</li>
          <li>• <strong>Developers:</strong> Those who want visual speed with option to customize</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">❌ Not For:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>E-commerce:</strong> Shopify is better for online stores</li>
          <li>• <strong>Beginners:</strong> Squarespace is easier if you have zero design experience</li>
          <li>• <strong>Bloggers:</strong> WordPress has better blogging features</li>
          <li>• <strong>Complex apps:</strong> Webflow or custom development for complex functionality</li>
          <li>• <strong>Budget-focused:</strong> Free builders exist if $15/month is too much</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Bottom Line -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <div class="bg-white bg-opacity-50 border-2 border-gray-300 rounded-xl p-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black mb-6">Bottom Line</h2>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">Framer is the modern website builder for designers. Visual interface, component-based design, fast performance. But it's not for everyone. E-commerce is weak. Learning curve exists. Template selection is limited.</p>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6"><strong>Choose Framer if:</strong></p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
        <li>• You're a designer who wants visual control</li>
        <li>• You use Figma and want to export designs directly</li>
        <li>• You're building portfolios, marketing sites, or landing pages</li>
        <li>• You care about performance and modern design</li>
        <li>• You're okay paying $15-25/month for serious sites</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6"><strong>Choose something else if:</strong></p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
        <li>• You need e-commerce → Use Shopify</li>
        <li>• You want something easier → Use Squarespace or Wix</li>
        <li>• You need more power → Use Webflow</li>
        <li>• You're blogging seriously → Use WordPress</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">Framer occupies a sweet spot: more visual than Webflow, more powerful than Squarespace, more performance-focused than Wix. You're paying for modern design workflow and fast sites. If that matches your needs, Framer delivers. If you need something else, there are better options. The free tier lets you test it out. Build a page, see if the interface clicks. If it does, you've found your website builder.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-6 text-gray-900">
      Related Reviews
    </h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <a href="/webflow-vs-wordpress" class="block bg-gray-50 hover:bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-6 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Webflow vs WordPress</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">No-code vs open source</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/bento-review" class="block bg-gray-50 hover:bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-6 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Bento Review</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">AI portfolio builder</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
